comments.body: @kelea99 I'm assuming we want it to look like it does in the Firefox screenshot in all browsers. Is this correct?
Correct, @sdellis . It looks odd dropping below the thumbnail to me.  What are your thoughts?
Yes, that's what I thought. I just wanted to double check!

@kelea99 Actually, I do have one thought... if the title is more than one line to the title, it looks strange, even in Firefox, as the thumbnails seem to float. I suggest we line them up with the top of the title block, like we do in the catalog. 

We also may want to think about putting the thumbnails on the left if we know we are going to have thumbnails and they provide enough information to the user to help them decide relevance. See: https://www.nngroup.com/articles/mobile-list-thumbnail/
I think we have items without thumbnails. In the East Asian tables of contents collection: https://dpul.princeton.edu/ealtoc/catalog?utf8=%E2%9C%93&exhibit_id=ealtoc&search_field=all_fields&q=
I would bet these are MVWs that did not have thumbnails selected for them in the parent, @hackartisan . checking EAL in figgy now and doing a test.

yup.  Test was an MVW. no thumbnail set on the children or selected in the parent. I set one and now it shows in DPUL: https://dpul.princeton.edu/ealtoc/catalog?utf8=%E2%9C%93&exhibit_id=ealtoc&search_field=all_fields&q=Ce+fu+yuan+gui+%2F+%5BWang+Qinruo+deng+bian%5D.
Right, I think they don't have thumbnails on purpose. We might ask Tom.
Music content doesn't have thumbnails, either.
